Frontline workers in the Western Cape are fast coming under attack from the coronavirus. The province now has almost a thousand cases and half of those are local transmissions. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Frontline workers in the Western Cape are fast coming under attack from the coronavirus. The province now has over 1,000 cases and half of those are local transmissions. In just three weeks, Khayelitsha in Cape Town has gone from registering just a single case to almost 60. READ: Western Cape mass screening, testing in full swing The province has the second-highest number of cases and the second-highest numbers of deaths in the country. The patient profile is shifting. From healthier, more affluent patients who had been travelling, the virus is now taking hold in Cape Town’s poorer communities. "The only people with legs at the moment are those who are working and that’s essential services, so that’s healthcare workers, supermarket workers and policemen, those manufacturing environments that are still functioning,” said University of Stellenbosch health expert Dr Kerrin Begg. READ: COVID-19: Western Cape 'preparing for the worst There are now more than 50 cases each in Mitchells Plain and Khayelitsha and also along the Klipfontein corridor. Begg says the worse yet to come. “Absolutely yes, our tsunami is still coming,” she added. Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.